 {"id":"franken_numpy-owxp","title":"[LOW] fnp-python 374 parity tests not organized as MUST/SHOULD conformance matrix","description":"per /testing-conformance-harnesses skill Pattern 4 (spec-derived test matrix): 'one test per MUST/SHOULD clause, tagged by requirement level'. fnp-python currently has 374 parity tests, each passes individually but they are not organized into a conformance matrix tagged by RequirementLevel (Must / Should / May).

Observed via cargo test -p fnp-python: tests named like <func>_matches_numpy_across_<scenarios> with assertions but no severity metadata. The fnp-conformance crate HAS this structure for Rust-core (Differential + Metamorphic + Adversarial × 14 domains = 2076+ cases with RequirementLevel tags).

Gap:
- No MUST/SHOULD tags on fnp-python tests
- No compliance matrix for fnp-python surface
- vhd5's audit reports coverage % (70.1% of numpy.__all__) but does not report TEST coverage vs what numpy.__all__ functions SHOULD do (edge cases, error surfaces, dtype preservation, etc.)

Proposed structure:
  #[must_clause] fn numpy_zeros_axis_default_dtype_is_float64_matches_numpy() { ... }
  #[should_clause] fn numpy_zeros_accepts_tuple_shape_arg() { ... }
  #[may_clause] fn numpy_zeros_order_F_column_major_layout_matches() { ... }

Then a compliance report generator counts pass/fail per level and produces a 'fnp-python MUST-coverage: 100% (X/X)' line.

Priority rationale: LOW — current 374-test battery catches regressions adequately. This is a classification/reporting improvement, not a testing gap. Would make the claim 'fnp-python is numpy-compatible at MUST level' rigorously verifiable.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-22T18:35:53.196666394Z","created_by":"cc-numpy","updated_at":"2026-04-24T00:21:29.754567971Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T00:21:29.752022931Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","organization","review"]}
